		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/06/world/06sino-TEXTILE/06sino-TEXTILE-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/06/world/06sino-TEXTILE/06sino-TEXTILE-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/06/world/06sino-TEXTILE/06sino-TEXTILE-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002916634" width="592" height="415" alt="AÂ garment factory in Jiujiang in central China&#039;s Jiangxi Province."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="415"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">AÂ garment factory in Jiujiang in central China's Jiangxi Province.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Uncredited/CHINATOPIX, via Associated Press</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//sinosphere.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/06/03/a-chic-idea-for-chinas-green-minded-set/" data-title="A Chic Idea for China&#8217;s Green-Minded Set" data-description="A Hong Kong-based environmental movement to clean up the textile and apparel industry is recruiting young talent to make the concept of eco fashion more attractive to the urban middle class in China.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div> A Hong Kong-based environmental movement to clean up the textile and apparel industry, one of the worldâs largest polluters, is recruiting young talent to make the concept of eco fashion more attractive to the urban middle class in China.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Since its creation in 2011, the <a title="award" href="//www.ecochicdesignaward.com">EcoChic Design Award</a> has challenged aspiring designers to create fashionable clothes with minimum waste. Winners are rewarded with opportunities to work with big brands that support their environmental agenda. This yearâs competition, which officially began on Tuesday in Hong Kong, is open to 10 regions in Asia and Europe, including mainland China, Taiwan, Malaysia, Sweden and Denmark.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And in a twist, on top of the sustainability requirements, applicants are being challenged to incorporate âChinese chicâ into their work, with an appeal to âa cosmopolitan Chinese woman,â according to the awardâs website, or an international woman with a taste for Chinese style, like a qipao, a Chinese dress popular in the 1930s and &#8217;40s.<br />
<span id="more-12011"></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This focus on China highlights the role it plays in the fashion world, but it will also help send an environmental message to a crucial audience, whose booming economy and embrace of fashion has made China both part of the problem of textile waste and, potentially, part of the solution, the awardâs organizers said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe are demonstratingâ to Chinese brands and consumers âthat sustainability is aspirational, luxury and high quality,â said Christina Dean, chief executive and founder of <a title="redress" href="//redress.com.hk">Redress</a>, the nongovernmental organization administering the award.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âChina does so much garment and textile production,â she added, saying that by engaging China, âwe hope it will have some ripple effectsâ across the industry.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The move comes as people in China are taking notice of environmental concerns, said Wang Haizhong, professor of consumer psychology and brand management at Sun Yat-Sen University in Guangzhou, capital of the southern province of Guangdong. That gives the contest a chance to have an immediate impact, he added.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âChinese consumers are increasingly aware of the environment,â Mr. Wang said. âA lot of affluent urbanites are now willing to spend more if they think it helps the earth. With recycled fashion, itâs just that they havenât realized itâs an environmental issue.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">China exported $284 billion worth of textile and apparel products in 2013, up 11.4 percent compared with 2012, according to the textile industry department of the <a title="report" href="//www.ccpittex.com/eng/news/59377.htm">China Council for the Promotion of International Trade</a> (CCPIT Tex). The trade group said exports reached $82 billion in January to April 2014.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Even as countries like Bangladesh are catching up to the worldâs major exporters, China still leads the game, accounting for more than 30 percent of the global exports of textile and apparel products, <a title="report" href="//www.ipe.org.cn/Upload/Report-Textiles-One-EN.pdf">according to a report</a> published in 2012 by five Chinese nonprofits documenting the environmental impacts of the countryâs textile and apparel industry.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Domestic consumption is strong as well. According to data from the National Bureau of Statistics of China, retail sales grew to 6.2 trillion renminbi, or about $1 trillion, in the first quarter of 2014, a 12 percent increase from the same period in 2013. That means the country must confront a growing problem of textile waste created both when garments are made and when they are discarded, experts said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The country produces over 20 million tons of such waste every year, said Gu Mingming, senior consultant at the China Association of Circular Economy. The figure is based on industry and consumer data over the past three years, like the volume of fibers processed in China and the number of abandoned garments.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Of this amount, only about â3 million tons are recycled, to produce new clothes or car interiors for example,â said Ms. Gu, who said the rest goes into incinerators or landfills.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Textile recycling can be difficult and costly. âSome clothes are built hard to recycle,â she said. âAll the zippers have to be manually removed and some dyes interfere with the chemical process.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Consumer resistance poses another hurdle.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe mainstream middle class in China still have a hard time accepting secondhand consumer goods,â especially clothes, Mr. Wang, the professor, said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Hygienic concerns and a cultural taboo that associates secondhand clothes with death stigmatize the idea of recycling. âA common mind-set is: âI donât want clothes that have been on strangers,ââ Mr. Wang added.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ms. Dean hopes her eco fashion initiative can help bring some change. A dentist-turned-journalist, Ms. Dean founded Redress in Hong Kong in 2007. Four years later, Redress introduced the design award.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âEducating fashion designers is an important step toward making the fashion industry sustainable,â Ms. Dean said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Applicants need to submit their designs by Aug. 15. Ten finalists, one from each region, will then compete for the top prize: a three-month work experience in Hong Kong, where they will design a collection for the eventâs prize partner, Shanghai Tang, using preconsumer textile waste collected from its factory floors. The luxury brand was founded in 1994 by the Hong Kong businessman David Tang and is now owned by the Switzerland-based luxury goods holding company Richemont.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThis will be the first time Shanghai Tang will produce a clothing line made using upcycled textiles from our own fabric surplus,â Raphael le Masne de Chermont, the companyâs executive chairman, said in an email.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Redress is betting on the younger generation in China â designers and consumers â coming around to recycling.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âA lot of Chinese consumers are still learning how to consume, if you will,â said Hannah Lane, Redressâs communications director. The award could be âa big opportunity to catch the hearts and minds of these people with more conscious purchasing decisions.â</p>
	</div>
